uiEntry.title: bg_title_frame
uiEntry.tooltip: This is where you create and break pacts with other nations, turning allies into enemies and foes into friends.||Move your cursor over the different sections below for more information.

uiEntry.title: title
uiEntry.tooltip: This is where you create and break pacts with other nations, turning allies into enemies and foes into friends.||Move your cursor over the different sections below for more information.

uiEntry.title: faction_title
uiEntry.tooltip: This panel contains all the diplomatic options open to you, along with relevant information on your nation.||Move your cursor over the different sections for more information.

uiEntry.title: leader_name_tx
uiEntry.tooltip: Your national leader.||A leader with skills in diplomacy will improve the chances of proposals being accepted.

uiEntry.title: power
uiEntry.tooltip: Your power is represented by your military strength.||The nations with the largest army and naval presence will be seen as the most powerful in the eyes of the world.||The more powerful you are the less popular you will be with other nations.

uiEntry.title: power_dy
uiEntry.tooltip: Your power is represented by your military strength.||The nations with the largest army and naval presence will be seen as the most powerful in the eyes of the world.||The more powerful you are the less popular you will be with other nations.

uiEntry.title: wealth
uiEntry.tooltip: Your wealth is based on your nation's income after costs.||Wealth is relative, and your position is measured against all other nation's riches.||If you are a wealthy nation you will be expected to be more generous in your offers.||Meagre offerings will not be looked on fondly and may ruin any negotiations.

uiEntry.title: wealth_dy
uiEntry.tooltip: Your wealth is based on your nation's income after costs.||Wealth is relative, and your position is measured against all other nation's riches.||If you are a wealthy nation you will be expected to be more generous in your offers.||Meagre offerings will not be looked on fondly and may ruin any negotiations.

uiEntry.title: protectorates
uiEntry.tooltip: These nations are under your protection.||In exchange for your protection you receive half their income and unlimited military access to their regions.

uiEntry.title: allies
uiEntry.tooltip: You can ask for support from these nations in the event of a war.||It is worth noting if your allies are enemies of the nation you are dealing with, as this could affect negotiations.||Your choice of allies may mean you have to try harder to gain the trust of the other nation.||You might even go as far as breaking one alliance to gain another - decide which nation will help you attain your goals!

uiEntry.title: trade_partners
uiEntry.tooltip: You have a trade partnership with these nations.

uiEntry.title: enemies
uiEntry.tooltip: Making enemies can be unavoidable, but try to choose your enemies as carefully as your friends.||If your share enemies with the nation you are negotiating with, they may see a common ground between you and be more open to your offers.

uiEntry.title: diplomacy_button
uiEntry.script:
local m_action = nil
function SetAction(a) m_action = a end
function Action() return m_action end
function EnterClickDown() local x,y = Component.Call("Position") Component.Call("Children[0].MoveTo", x+2, y+2) end
function ExitClickDown() local x,y = Component.Call("Position") Component.Call("Children[0].MoveTo", x+1, y+1) end
function NotifySelected() Component.CallByAddress(Component.GetProperty("Notify"), "LuaCall", "Notify", Component.FindChildAddress("button_tx")) end

state.title: state_gift
state.tooltip: Do this as a sign of goodwill - particularly if your relations with this nation are a little strained.

state.title: access
state.tooltip: Click here to negotiate military access requests or demands.||If one nation wants to move their army into another nation's territory they have two choices: either declare war or ask for military access.||Military access is not a permission given lightly.||A good diplomatic relationship between the two nations is a necessity.||Allowing another nation's army into your region could leave you vulnerable to an attack by them.||It also exposes your region to their scrutiny.||Click this button to see the military access panel and more details.

state.title: access_cancel
state.tooltip: You have currently granted this nation military access, and as such they can move their armies where you have allowed.||This can leave you vulnerable to surprise attacks and if you are beginning to distrust their intentions you may want to cancel their access.||You will also have to cancel military access if you want to declare war.||Do not act rashly, if your relationship with them is strong, cancelling this may damage your alliance.||Check public opinion towards this nation and vice versa to get an idea of your relationship.

state.title: payments
state.tooltip: Click here to demand or offer payments.||Money plays a key role in diplomacy.||Offer it as a sign of goodwill, a bribe to get your own way, or demand it in exchange for granting requests.||The bigger the request the more money you can ask for - of course you could ask for technology or a region instead.||Clicking here will bring up the payments panel with more information.

state.title: protector
state.tooltip: Request the other nation come under your protection.||Though it may sound like extra work, becoming a nation's protector can actually have many advantages.||You will receive half of their income and gain unlimited military access to their regions.||When a nation becomes protectorate they must break all previous alliances.||Protectorate nations can still declare war on other nations - if this happens you will be dragged into the conflict.

state.title: regions
state.tooltip: Click here to offer or demand regions.||Regions can be offered or demanded as part of peace negotiations, or even as gifts between friendly nations.||A regions value is assessed according to its income and strategic value in the game.||Clicking this button will bring up the regions panel.

state.title: protector_cancel
state.tooltip: You are currently a protectorate of this nation, but is the relative security worth the loss of your independence?||At the moment half of your nation's income is paid out in exchange for their protection.||They also have unlimited military access across all your regions.||If you choose to stand alone they will need military access to travel within your regions.

state.title: trade_cancel
state.tooltip: This will close all trade routes between the two nations.||You will lose any trade income from this nation if you cancel this.

state.title: peace
state.tooltip: You are currently at war with this nation.||If this nation has strong trade resources it may be advantageous to make peace and become a trade partner rather than an enemy.

state.title: war
state.tooltip: This will bring up a declare war panel where you can see potential allies for both sides.

state.title: technology
state.tooltip: Click here to open up the negotiation panel for technologies.||Technology is important for the development of your nation's buildings and armies, among other things.||You must research a technology before it can be offered or demanded.||Clicking this button will bring up another panel that has more details.

state.title: alliance_cancel
state.tooltip: If you do this you will lose all the advantages that come with an alliance.||You may wish to do this if your ally has an enemy you want to impress.

state.title: alliance
state.tooltip: Click here to request an alliance with the other nation.||In the event of a battle you can call upon your allied nations to aid you.||Don't count on them too much though - they may refuse!

state.title: trade
state.tooltip: A trade agreement will open up a trade route between the two nations.||The goods you export along trade routes will contribute towards your trade income.

uiEntry.title: faction_title
uiEntry.tooltip: This panel contains all the diplomatic information of the nation you are negotiating with.||These details can help inform your diplomatic decisions.||Mouse over the areas below for more information.

uiEntry.title: leader_name_banner
uiEntry.tooltip: This is the leader of the nation you are negotiating with.||Right-clicking on their portrait will bring up their details panel, which will provide you with more specific details about them.||Much like your leader, their diplomatic skills may affect negotiations and the deals you are able to make.

uiEntry.title: leader_name_tx
uiEntry.tooltip: This is the leader of the nation you are negotiating with.||Their diplomatic skills may affect negotiations and the deals you are able to make.

uiEntry.title: protectorates
uiEntry.tooltip: Protectorates are nations who come under the protection of another nation.||In exchange for protection the protectorate grants full access to its regions, and pays the protecting nation half its income.

uiEntry.title: allies
uiEntry.tooltip: Military alliances can help or hinder diplomatic negotiations.||If some of their allies are also your allies, they will have common ground with you, earning you a little more trust.||This can work the other way though - if their allies are your enemies you may have to work harder in negotiations.

uiEntry.title: trade_partners
uiEntry.tooltip: Trade partners are nations with trade routes between them.

uiEntry.title: enemies
uiEntry.tooltip: A shared enemy is a sign that you are both on the same page and may prove useful in gaining this nation's trust.||On the other hand, if you are allied with one of their enemies you may be viewed with suspicion.

uiEntry.title: public_opinion
uiEntry.tooltip: Successful negotiations rely on many factors, but this is a useful hint as to how this nation may react to your offers.||The friendlier they are toward you, the more likely they are to accept your proposals.||Try getting the people on your side by offering a state gift, or a one off payment.||Public opinion will change according to your actions.

uiEntry.title: public_opinion_dy
uiEntry.tooltip: Successful negotiations rely on many factors, but this is a useful hint as to how this nation may react to your offers.||The friendlier they are toward you, the more likely they are to accept your proposals.||Try getting the people on your side by offering a state gift, or a one off payment.||Public opinion will change according to your actions.

uiEntry.title: treaties
uiEntry.tooltip: Before making any offers or demands, you may want to check this section.||If you already hold treaties with this faction it may affect your choices in negotiations.||For example, if they have granted you military access you do not want to do anything that would cause them to distrust you, or you could lose it.

uiEntry.title: treaties_title
uiEntry.tooltip: Before making any offers or demands, you may want to check this section.||If you already hold treaties with this nation it may affect your choices in negotiations.||For example, if they have granted you military access you do not want to do anything that would cause them to distrust you, or you could lose it.

state.title: faction_right
state.tooltip: Balance their demands against their offers to make sure you're getting a good deal.||Think about your relations with this nation before accepting or refusing any proposals.||If you want them as a friend, try to find an acceptable agreement for you both.||However, if you have no use for them, you can be more demanding without worrying about angering them.

state.title: faction_left
state.tooltip: This section shows all the offers you are making as part of your diplomatic proposal. || Use the buttons to the left to make offers which will get added here. || Your demands are shown to the right to make it simpler for you to compose a balanced proposal. || Once you have finished, click on the send proposal button. || You can remove offers or demands by clicking on the cross next to them if you have changed your mind.

state.title: faction_right
state.tooltip: Balance their offers against their demands to make sure you're getting a good deal.||If they are a rich nation any money offers should be generous.||If you are not happy with the offers you can make a counteroffer.

state.title: faction_left
state.tooltip: This section shows all the demands you are making as part of your diplomatic proposal. || Use the buttons to the far-left to make demands which will get added here. || Your offers are shown to the left to make it simpler for you to compose a balanced proposal. || Once you have finished, click on the send proposal button. || You can remove offers or demands by clicking on the cross next to them.

uiEntry.title: map_placeholder
uiEntry.tooltip: Regions map||This depicts the regions owned by your nation and the nation you are negotiating with.||Your nation's regions are coloured in green, whereas theirs are coloured red.||Using this map you can see strategic positions more clearly.||Mousing over the regions marked on the map will tell you their names so you can choose them from the two panels below.||Switch to another theatre view by using the scrolling buttons below.

uiEntry.title: button_threat_of_force
uiEntry.tooltip: Threaten||Some nations may need a little extra persuasion to accept your generous offers.||Use this to impress upon them the dangers of turning you down, but be aware this may sour relations with them.||Bigger is better.||The more powerful you are, the more weight your threats will carry.
uiEntry.script:
local this = UIComponent(Address) local parent = UIComponent(this:Parent("diplomacy_panel"))
function OnSelect() parent:LuaCall("ThreatOfForce") end

uiEntry.title: button_send
uiEntry.tooltip: Send proposal||When you have finished balancing your offers and demands, select this button to send the proposal to the other nation.||If you change your mind about any aspect of your proposal you can either left-click on individual offers and demands or press the clear offer button to the right.||Once you have sent the proposal the other nation will respond, either positively, negatively or with a counteroffer.||Their representative will make it clear how they feel about the negotiations and how your relations currently stand.||Just because they accept a proposal doesn't mean they are necessarily happy about it!

uiEntry.tooltip: Presenting a gift helps to improve relations between nations.||If their public opinion of you is poor this gift may help turn things around.||Giving a gift is not part of diplomatic bartering - although they can help smooth the way for precisely that.||There are three types of gifts to offer - each ascending in value.||When offering a gift, take your own wealth into account.||If you are wealthy it won't look sincere if you skimp on the gift!
Finest china||Present some of your finest china to show goodwill.
Thoroughbred||Offer one of your thoroughbreds, a racing horse and a fine prize.
Jewellery||Send a gift of jewellery to demonstrate the worth you place on your friendship.
